{"cursor":"13543","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'fluctuation-dissipation theorem' ('FDT') is a powerful tool in statistical\nphysics for predicting the behavior of non-equilibrium thermodynamical systems.\nThese systems involve the irreversible dissipation of energy into heat from\ntheir reversible thermal fluctuations at thermodynamic equilibrium. The fluctuation-\ndissipation theorem applies both to classical and quantum mechanical systems.\n\nThe fluctuation-dissipation theorem relies on the assumption that the response\nof a system in thermodynamic equilibrium to a small applied force is the same as\nits response to a spontaneous fluctuation. Therefore, the theorem connects the\nlinear response relaxation of a system from a prepared non-equilibrium state to\nits statistical fluctuation properties in equilibrium. {{cite book |author\n= David Chandler |year=1987 |title=Introduction to Modern Statistical Mechanics\n|page=255 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-504277-1 }}\nOften the linear response takes the form of one or more exponential decays.\n\nThe fluctuation-dissipation theorem was originally formulated by Harry Nyquist\nin 1928, {{cite journal\n | author = Nyquist H year = 1928 title = Thermal Agitation of Electric Charge\n | in Conductors journal = Physical Review volume = 32 | pages = 110–113\n | bibcode = 1928PhRv...32..110N doi = 10.1103/PhysRev.32.110\n }} and later proven by Herbert Callen and Theodore A. Welton in\n 1951. {{cite journal |author = H.B. Callen, T.A. Welton\n | year = 1951 title = Irreversibility and Generalized Noise journal = Physical\n | Review volume = 83 | pages = 34–40 bibcode = 1951PhRv...83...34C doi =\n | 10.1103/PhysRev.83.34\n}}\n","linknr":255,"url":"Fluctuation_dissipation_theorem","recorded":1375088863,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Fluctuation-dissipation_theorem&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Fluctuation-dissipation_theorem&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico",